{
  "texts": [
    "All proofs are provided in Section C. Statement of Technical ResultsWe begin with the definition of the inverse permutation function.Definition 1 (Inverse permutation function).",
    "For fixed n, a permutation matrix P ∈ {0, 1} n×n is defined such that ith row represents the elementary unit vector e π(i) for some permutation π(•).",
    "For any n-row matrix Y P, the inverse permutation function outputs Y = P -1 Y P.We interpret each row of Y P as corresponding to the embedding of a single token in the (permuted) input, and each row of Y as corresponding to the embedding of a single token of the (canonical) output.Observe that one function satisfying Definition 1 is the trivial linear transformation (P, Y P) → P ⊤ Y P, since P -1 = P ⊤.",
    "As mentioned above, this task is arguably simpler than the more realistic tasks which motivate it: the description of the permutation P is given explicitly, rather than being determined by some function of the permuted input Y P (e.g., its lexicographic index).",
    "Thus, we have eliminated the difficulty of determining the order in which inputs are arranged or the choice of canonical ordering during internal model computations."
  ]
}